<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06102193 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06102193 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  US; AUTO; MANUFACTURING; COMPANY; STOCK; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Ford Motor Co.'s stock dividend comes up for review today, and analysts werepredicting the 75-cent quarterly dividend would be chopped by half or more.;   The meeting of the automaker's board of directors comes less than a monthbefore Ford's annual meeting. If the dividend is halved, it would save thecompany about $704.5 million on an annual basis.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  FORD EXPECTED TO CUT DIVIDEND  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The last time Ford lowered its dividend was when it eliminated italtogether in the first quarter of 1982, when the industry was suffering froma recession.;    Earlier this year, General Motors Corp. cut its 75-centquarterly dividend to 40 cents and Chrysler Corp. halved its 30-cent-a-sharequarterly dividend.;    Each of the Big Three has initiated cost-cuttingprograms aimed at slashing billions of dollars from their expenses.;    Theseprograms and other problems, including the recession and the Persian Gulf war,have put the Big Three under pressure to cut their dividends, which arequarterly payouts to shareholders.;    &quot;I think you would be ignoring somesignals if you thought (Ford) would pay the regular dividend,&quot; said autoanalyst David Healy of the investment banker Barclays de Zoete Wedd in NewYork.;    &quot;I think they will cut the dividend probably at least in half, maybetwo-thirds,&quot; he said.;    Ford last year reported earnings of $860 million,down 77 percent from 1989 earnings of $3.8 billion. Revenue grew slightly, to$97.7 billion from $96.1 billion.;    The automaker resisted pressure lastJanuary to cut the quarterly dividend. However, one month later its Canadiansubsidiary, Ford of Canada, eliminated its dividend.;    That subsidiary,which makes some of the company's most profitable cars and pickup trucks,reported a loss of about $48.5 million for 1990.;    In February, GM cut itsdividend, saving the company about $842 million on a yearly basis, and inMarch, Chrysler halved its dividend, resulting in a $134.6 million annualsaving.;    In the mid-1980s, when the auto industry was booming and Ford wasreporting industry-record profits, the automaker decided against raising itsdividend, figuring it was better to maintain a steady level of shareholderpayouts rather than raise it only to lower it later.;    &quot;They had beentelling the story of how they were using the dividend sustainability theory sothat when they could have afforded to increase it they didn't; so that whenthey had to cut it they didn't have to,&quot; said auto analyst Charles Brady ofBrenner Securities Group Inc. of New York.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Detroit  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910411  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  412  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday April 11, 199100102193,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>